    <subfield code="f">1847-2008.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="300" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">19 linear feet, 3 oversize volumes, and 2 phonograph record albums.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="545" ind1="1" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">The First Congregational Church of Ann Arbor, Michigan, was organized and established on March 23, 1847. Lloyd C. Douglas was one-time pastor of the church.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">The records of the First Congregational Church of Ann Arborhave been divided into the following series: History/Background Information; Administration; Financial Records; Church Organizations; Topical Files; Miscellaneous later records; Photographs; Publications; and Phonograph records. The records document church administration, membership activities, and the relationship of the church to its denomination and to other area churches. Included are records of communicants, baptisms and marriages (1873-1905); pew subscriptions and accounts (1878-1939) and other membership information; minutes and reports of the board of trustees and the church council; records of men's and women's church groups such as the King's Daughters, the Ladies Aid Society, the Women's Fellowship Society, and the Women's Foreign Missionary Society; records relating to the church's affiliation with the Ann Arbor-Washtenaw Council of Churches; and files pertaining to the proposed merger of the Evangelical and Reformed Church with the Congregational Church in the 1950s.</subfield>
  </datafield>
